        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you for your very kind letter which I value much as coming from you who have done such excellent scientific work.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Also pray accept my thanks for the gift of your book on Smyrna, &amp; for sending me the Vienna newspaper with its too generous appreciation of my character.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I shall be in London in the Spring &amp; I will then find out where the Austro-Hungarian Consulate is, &amp; do myself the pleasure &amp; honour of calling on you.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> My health is weak &amp; there is no direct railway from here to Norwood<ref target="#foot.f5"/> &amp; the drive by the road is a long one; otherwise I w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have called on you there. For this same reason I cannot venture to ask you to come here some day to luncheon, which would give me much pleasure, although I am not able to converse with anyone for more than a rather short time.</p>
<p>With my respect &amp; best thanks, I remain | Dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">2.3 by the road 2.4] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the date of the inscription in CD’s copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8994.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Scherzer 1873</ref> (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Scherzer’s letter has not been found; CD had referred in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 216 to population data gathered by Scherzer during the voyage of the <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5916.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Novara</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8994.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Scherzer 1873</ref>, inscribed by the author and dated 21 January 1876, is in the Darwin Library–Down; Scherzer had been Austrian consul in Smyrna (now Izmir), Turkey, before being transferred to London in July 1875 (<hi rend="italic">Morning Post</hi>, 8 July 1875, p. 2). The Viennese newspaper has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">No record has been found of a visit by CD to the Austrian Consulate.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Norwood, Surrey, is a southern suburb of London.</note>
        </div>        
            
